## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker` Component

There are **three compounding bugs** that together cause a catastrophic accumulation of event listeners.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Re-registers on Every Render)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
}); // ← no second argument!
```

Without a dependency array, `useEffect` runs **after every single render**. Since the scroll and resize handlers call `setState`, they trigger a re-render, which triggers the effect again, which adds more listeners, which trigger more state updates, and so on.

**The lifecycle of the bug:**

```
Mount → effect runs → 2 listeners added (total: 2)
User scrolls → handler fires → setState → re-render
→ effect runs again → 2 more listeners added (total: 4)
→ all 4 handlers fire → 4 setState calls → re-render
→ effect runs again → 2 more listeners added (total: 6)
→ exponential growth...
```

Each navigation away and back to the page starts a new accumulation cycle on top of whatever survived from the last visit (due to Bug #2).

---

## Bug #2 — Missing Cleanup Function (Listeners Are Never Removed)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ← no return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

React's `useEffect` cleanup mechanism works like this:

```
Component mounts   → effect runs (setup)
Component unmounts → cleanup function runs (teardown)
Effect re-runs     → previous cleanup runs first, then new setup
```

Without a cleanup function, **no listeners are ever removed**. When the user navigates away, React unmounts the component, but the listeners remain attached to `window` — a global object that lives for the entire page session. They hold references to React state setter functions (closures), preventing garbage collection of the old component instances' state.

Navigate away and back 10 times → **20+ zombie listeners** still firing on every scroll event, trying to update state that no longer exists.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

Even if someone tried to add cleanup, this pattern makes it impossible:

```jsx
// These two functions are NOT the same reference:
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { setScrollY(...) });
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { setScrollY(...) }); // ← does NOTHING
```

`removeEventListener` works by **reference equality**. Every `() => {}` expression creates a brand-new function object. To remove a listener, you must pass the **exact same function reference** that was passed to `addEventListener`.

```jsx
// This works:
const handler = () => { setScrollY(...) };
window.addEventListener('scroll', handler);
window.removeEventListener('scroll', handler); // ✅ same reference
```

---

## Bug #3b — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

There's a fourth, subtler bug. `lastScrollY` is held in state, so handlers capture its value at the time they're created. In the corrected version with `[]`, the handler is created once at mount — meaning `lastScrollY` in the closure is always `0`. The `setLastScrollY` calls update state, but the handler never sees the new value.

The fix is to use a `useRef` for `lastScrollY`, which gives a mutable container that handlers always read the latest value from, without causing re-renders.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Worse in Development

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects** to help surface exactly this type of bug:

```
Mount → effect runs (setup)
↓ [Strict Mode only]
Immediate simulated unmount → cleanup runs (or doesn't, if missing)
Re-mount → effect runs again (setup)
```

If cleanup is missing, you'll see **2 sets of listeners** immediately on first mount during development. This is intentional — React is stress-testing your cleanup. If your component handles Strict Mode's double-invoke correctly (cleanup removes what setup added), it handles real unmounts correctly too.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // useRef instead of useState: gives handlers the latest value
    // without causing re-renders or stale closure issues
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named functions so we can pass the exact same reference
        // to both addEventListener and removeEventListener
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // ref reads/writes are always current — no stale closure
            setScrollDirection(
                currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up'
            );
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup function: runs on unmount AND before each re-run of
        // this effect. Removes the exact same references that were added.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // Empty array: run once on mount, clean up once on unmount.
            // No dependencies needed because we use a ref for lastScrollY.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Original | Fixed |
|---|---|---|
| Effect re-runs | Every render (no `[]`) | Once on mount (`[]`) |
| Listener cleanup | Never removed | `return () => removeEventListener(...)` |
| Function references | Anonymous (unremovable) | Named variables (removable) |
| Stale `lastScrollY` | State (stale in closure) | `useRef` (always current) |

The corrected component will have **exactly 2 listeners** attached at all times during its lifetime, and **0 listeners** after it unmounts — regardless of how many times the user navigates away and back.

